Total.js framework supports a simple authorization mechanism. It's built on the one delegate function [`AUTH(function($))`](/total4/407ff001jy51c/#4893f001wa51c). The authorization is asynchronous.

< __Good to know__: All requests (with WebSocket) are evaluated in [`AUTH()`](/total4/407ff001jy51c/#4893f001wa51c) delegate, except requests of static files. The delegate is executed during the request processing and determines if the request is authorized or not.

The diagram below shows how Total.js authorization works:<br><br>

![Authorization](/download/94vb002wg40d-54u2st-650x206-1.png)

## Example

The example below describes how easily you can write your authorization mechanism. Total.js doesn't limit you. The below `AUTH()` declaration is used for both classic HTTP requests and WebSockets.

```js
var sessions = {};

AUTH(function($) {

	// You will execute this function for each request with except request to a static file
	// It's on you how you authorization the request

	var cookie = $.cookie('ssid');

	if (!cookie) {

		// Request is unauthorized
		$.invalid();
		return;

	}

	var session = sessions[cookie];
	if (session) {

		// Request is authorized
		$.success(session);
		return;

	}

	DBMS().read('tbl_user').where('token', cookie).callback(function(err, response) {

		if (response) {

			// Request is authorized
			// We store a user profile in "sessions" variable due to performance
			sessions[cookie] = response;
			$.success(response);

		} else {

			// Request is unauthorized
			$.invalid();

		}

	});

});

// The service below clears all sessions in 5 minutes interval
ON('service', function(counter) {

	if (counter % 5 === 0)
		sessions = {};

});
```

__Usage in controllers__:

```js
exports.install = function() {
	ROUTE('+GET    /account/         *Account         --> @profile');
	ROUTE('-POST   /account/login/   *Acccount/Login  --> @exec');
	ROUTE('GET     /privacy/');
}
```

- `+` means that the request must be authorized
- `-` means that the request must be unauthorized
- without `+` or `-` means that it doesn't matter if the request is authorized or not

---

Your authorization mechanism can use everything, and it's independent of the storage, so you can use `Redis`, `MongoDB`, `CouchDB`, `PostgreSQL`, `MySQL`, etc. - it doesn't matter.

We prepared some predefined tools for handling of sessions, read more in [`AUTH()` method](/total4/407ff001jy51c/#4893f001wa51c).

< :far fa-exclamation-triangle: __IMPORTANT__<br>`AUTH()` must return only if the request is authorized or unauthorized. Don't perform redirect or other operations in this method.

Tasks allow you to customize and extendthe Total.js framework, and they are targeted at exceptional cases. Tasks are very versatile because they can execute infinitely between themself.

::: Example

```js
NEWTASK('Download', function(push) {

	push('init', function($) {
		// you can extend "$" by your needs:
		$.output = [];
		$.next('delay');
	});

	push('delay', function($) {
		setTimeout($.next2('download'), 1000);
	});

	push('download', function($, value) {

		// value is alias for "$.value"

		var url = value.shift();
		if (url == null) {
			// End of TaskBuilder and send the value to the callback
			$.end($.output);
			return;
		}

		RESTBuilder.GET(url).callback(function(err, response, output) {

			if (err) {
				// Unhandled error
				// Go back
				$.value.push(url);
			} else
				$.output.push(output.response);

			$.next('delay');
		});

	});

});

// Run task
TASK('Download/init', function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
}, null, ['https://www.totaljs.com', 'https://www.google.com', 'https://nodejs.org']);
```

:::

