Total.js Components are beneficial for extending existing projects. They have very simple declaration. Each component contains only __single file declaration__, which means that the component is only a single HTML file with CSS, client-side script, server-side script, and HTML.

- [Learn from example](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/tree/master/components)

__Features__:

- supports the server-side implementation
- supports inline declaring of static files
- supports rendering of all components by group name
- also supports partial rendering

__Good to know__:

- component is a single `.html` file stored in `/components/` directory
- components are rendered in `views`
- components support localization `@(Translate me)`
- styles and scripts from components are moved to independent static files
- all inline `.html` files will be localized and minified

## Example

__Declaration `/components/newsletter.html`__:

```html
<!-- Server-side script -->
<script total>

	// Optional
	exports.group = 'Name of group';

	// Optional
	exports.install = function() {
		ROUTE('POST /api/newsletter/', function() {
			var self = this;
			var model = self.body;
			model.ip = self.ip;
			model.dtcreated = NOW;
			NOSQL('newsletter').insert(self.body).callback(self.done());
		});
	};

	// Optional
	// Asynchronous rendering
	exports.render = function($) {

		// $.repository
		// $.model
		// $.user
		// $.session
		// $.controller
		// $.query
		// $.body
		// $.files
		// $.options, $.settings --> will contain same value
		// $.callback(model); --> callback with model

		// !!! IMPORTANT !!!
		// "$.callback" must return a model which will be used for the component "view"

		// For example:
		NOSQL('products').find().take(10).callback((err, response) => $.callback(response));
	};

</script>

<!-- CSS -->
<style>
	.newsletter { padding: 50px; background-color: #D0D0D0; border-radius: 4px; }
	.newsletter-input { font-size: 20px; padding: 20px; width: 100%; }
	.newsletter-success { padding: 50px; background-color: green; border-radius: 4px; color: white; }
</style>

<!-- HTML which will be rendered -->
<div class="newsletter">
	<div>Join to newsletter @{settings.key}:</div>
	<input type="text" class="newsletter-input" placeholder="Type your email address" />
</div>

<!-- Client-side script -->
<script>
	$(document).on('keypress', '.newsletter-input', function(e) {
		if (e.keyCode == 13) {
			var el = $(this).closest('.newsletter');
			AJAX('POST /api/newsletter/', { email: this.value }, function(response) {
				el.replaceWith('<div class="newsletter-success">THANK YOU!</div>');
			});
		}
	});
</script>
```

__Rendering in views__:

```html
<h2>Newsletter 1</h2>

<!-- Renders the component with a custom settings -->
@{component('newsletter', { key: 'Custom settings value', something: 100 })}

<h2>Newsletter 2</h2>

<!-- Renders the component without settings -->
@{component('newsletter')}
```

Registers a new global operation.

```js
NEWOPERATION(name, fn, [repeat], [stop], [bind_error], [queryschema]);
// @name {String} An operation name.
// @fn {Function($)} An operation context.
// @repeat {Number} How many times can this operation be repeated if this operation will throw an error?
// @stop {Boolean} If true, then it won't execute the next operations. This argument is applied for RUN() method (default: true)
// @bind_error {Boolean} If true, then an error (if it throws) will be returned from this operation when operations are chaining. Otherwise, the framework returns value or undefined
// @queryschema {String} A predefined schema for query arguments. It must be in the form key:Type,page:Number,limit:Number,search:String. The parser uses CONVERT() method internally
```

__Example__:

```js
NEWOPERATION('myoperation', function($, value) {

	// "$" for more info look to "$" section
	// @value {Object} alias for "$.value"

	$.success();

}, 3);
```

__Example with a query filter:__

```
NEWOPERATION('myoperation', function($, value) {

	// "$.filter" inherits values from $.query and the values are transformed according to the query schema:
	console.log($.filter);
	// Example of output: --> { page: 1, limit: 100, q: '' }

	$.success();

}, 'page:Number, limit:Number, q:String');
```

`PREF` is meant as user preferences. You can customize preferences; in other words: you can affect behavior for reading/writing preferences. __Loading/Saving__ is performed automatically by the framework.

`PREF` is a global variable. Data are read from `PREF` via `PREF.yourkey` with except some reserved keywords.

---

`PREF` behavior for reading/writing values from/to `PREF` can be rewritten with delegates defined in:

- [__DEF.onPrefLoad__](/total4/407ff001jy51c/#72109001oa51c)
- [__DEF.onPrefSave__](/total4/407ff001jy51c/#7210c001hu51c)

::: How to store preferences in DB?

- [How to store Total.js configuration in PostgreSQL?](/dbms/61e1a001fn51c/#61e24001ym51c)

__Example__:

```js
DEF.onPrefSave = function(data) {
	DBMS().modify('cl_config', { id: 'preferences', value: JSON.stringify(data), dtupdated: NOW }, true).id('preferences');
};

DEF.onPrefLoad = function(next) {
	DBMS().read('cl_config').where('id', 'preferences').fields('value').callback(function(err, response) {
		next((response ? (response.value || '').parseJSON(true) : null) || {});
	});
};
```
:::

