The method executes a method according to the path. It wont't throw any exception if the method does not exist. Supports execution of:

- `method` according the path
- `plugins`
- `events`
- `commands`
- `components`
- supports environments

```js
EXEC([wait], path, [a], [b], [..n]);
// @wait {Boolean} enables a waiter for the method instance (if method doesn't exist)
// @path {String}
// @a {Object} Optional, additional argument
// @b {Object} Optional, additional argument
// @..n {Object} Optional, additional argument

EXEC('users_refresh');
// Executes --> window.users_refresh();

EXEC('users_refresh', true);
// Executes --> window.users_refresh(true);

EXEC('#submit', true);
// Executes --> EMIT('submit', true);

EXEC('&flow.refresh');
// Executes --> CMD('flow.refresh');

EXEC('-loading/hide', 1000);
// +v19
// Executes --> SETTER('loading/hide', 1000);

EXEC('PLUGIN/method_name');
```

This is a beneficial method. It can evaluate some actions in schemas, like in routing. It supports all form HTTP methods for CRUD operations.

If you don't assign any controller, then the method creates a virtual controller that allows you to set custom, e.g. user instance.

```js
EXEC(schema, model, callback, [controller]);
// @schema {String}
// @model {Object}
// @callback {Function}
// @controller {$/Controller}
// returns {Controller}
```

## How to call schemas?

__Good to know__:

- `+` (POST/PUT) enables validation for the entire model, example: `+Schema --> operation`
- `#` (PATCH) enables partial validation, example: `#Schema --> operation`
- `-` (GET/DELETE) validation is disabled, example: `-Schema --> operation`

__Examples__:

```js
EXEC('+Products --> check save (response)', { name: 'Total.js' }, function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});

EXEC('-Products --> read', function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});

// Or you can execute the method in the form:

EXEC('POST Products --> check save (response)', { name: 'Total.js' }, function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});

EXEC('GET Products --> read', function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});

// NEW: supports Query arguments
EXEC('-Products --> read ?name=Total', function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});
```

__Example Async/Await__:

```js
await EXEC('-Products --> read');
await EXEC('-Products --> read', null, { id: '12345' });
// third argument can have "controller" variables like "id", "params" or "query"
```

__How to assign user object or query arguments?__

```js
var controller = EXEC('-Users --> query', { name: 'Total.js' }, function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});

controller.query = { fields: 'id,name' };
controller.user = { name: 'Peter', sa: true };
```

__What else can I use?__

- `controller.id` sets `$.id`
- `controller.params` sets `$.params`
- `controller.user` sets `$.user`


## How to call Tasks?

__Examples__:

```js
EXEC('Task/task_operation', { name: 'Total.js' }, function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});
```


## How to call Operations?

__Examples__:

```js
EXEC('operation_name', { name: 'Total.js' }, function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});
```

Performs `UPDATE` for the specific fields. A response is a number with count of modified documents.

```js
// db.modify(name, doc, [insert]);
// @name {String} A collection/table name
// @doc {Object} A document
// @insert {Boolean} Performs "insert" if the document won't exist.
// returns QueryBuilder
// response: Number

db.modify('users', { '+age': 1, dateupdated: NOW }, true).where('name', 'Peter');

// Supports incremental values
// +prop performs val + 1
// -prop performs val - 1
// *prop performs val * 1
// /prop performs val / 1
// >prop performs Math.max(dbval, val);
// <prop performs Math.min(dbval, val);

// Supports toggles (supported in PostgreSQL)
// { '!prop': 1 }
// Performs "prop = !prop"

// Raw values (supported in PostgreSQL)
// { '=now': 'NOW()' }
// Performs "now=NOW()"

// Raw values (supported in PostgreSQL), but the value will be skipped for INSERT!!!
// { '#now': 'NOW()' }
// Performs "now=NOW()"

// +v0.7.7
// Read/Modify feature:
db.modify('users', function(doc, output, responses) {

	// @doc {Object}
	// @output {Object} a current output
	// @responses {Object} an object with all responses

	// doc can be "null" if you the "insert" param is "true"
	// DBMS will update only the fields declared below
	return { name: doc.name.toUpperCase() };

	// This skips updateting:
	// return null;

}).where('id', 123456).fields('name');
```

