The method creates a TCP connection.

- supports TLS
- supports secure connection

```js
U.connect(opt, callback);
// @opt {Object} a custom options
// @callback {Functon(err, meta)}
```

__Options__:

- `opt.host {String}` IP address or hostname
- `opt.port {Number}` a port number
- `opt.secure {Boolean}` optional, creates a secure connection
- `opt.tls {Object}` optional, TLS options (experimental)
	- `tls.host {String}`
	- `tls.port {Number}`
	- `tls.ciphers {String}` optional

__`meta` properties__:

- `meta.socket {Socket}` socket for communication (alias to `socket1` or `socket2`)
- `meta.socket1 {Socket}`
- `meta.socket2 {Socket}` optional, TLS layer
- `meta.write(buffer/string) {Function}` writes a data to the current socket
- `meta.destroy() {Function}` destroys the connection
- `meta.ondata = function(fn) {Function}` on data handler
- `meta.onend = function(fn) {Function}` on end handler

### A simple example

```js
var opt = {};
opt.host = '127.0.0.1';
opt.port = 80;
U.connect(opt, function(err, meta) {

	meta.ondata(function(data) {
		console.log(data);
	});

});
```

This method joins links/paths to the one.

```js
U.link(path1, [path2], [path3]);
