This method registers a trigger. The trigger is a beneficial helper for communication between the client-side and server-side.

< :far fa-warning: You can register Trigger directly in the Flow component declaration. [Learn from __HttpReceiver__ component](https://github.com/totaljs/flowcomponents/blob/master/httpreceiver/httpreceiver.js#L61) - look to registering and unregistering.

```js
FLOW.trigger(name, callback);
// @name {String} name of trigger
// @callback {Function(next, data)} optional
```

__Registering trigger__:

```js
FLOW.trigger('something', function(next, data) {
	// do something
});
```

__Unregistering trigger__:

```js
FLOW.trigger('something', null);
```

### Example

__Server-side declaration__:

```js
FLOW.trigger('name', function(next, data) {

	// @next {Function(data)}
	// @data {Object}

	// Data received from client-side
	console.log(data);

	// Sends back another data
	next([1, 2, 3, 4]);
});
```

__Client-side usage__:

```js
// Calls a trigger
TRIGGER('name', function(data) {
	console.log(data); // outputs [1, 2, 3, 4]
});

// Or calls a trigger with jComponent auto-binding:
TRIGGER('name', 'path.to.bind.response');
// A response will be binded automaticaly to: "window.path.to.bind.response"
```

