It's very easy, you need to extend WebSocket routing like this:

```js
exports.install = function() {

	// API routes
	ROUTE('API  @api   -users_query            *Users    --> query');
	ROUTE('API  @api   -users_read/{id}        *Users    --> read');
	ROUTE('API  @api   +users_insert           *Users    --> check insert (response)');
	ROUTE('API  @api   +users_update/{id}      *Users    --> update');
	ROUTE('API  @api   -users_remove/{id}      *Users    --> remove');

	// Main socket:
	ROUTE('SOCKET /myendpoint/', socket);
};

function socket() {
	var self = this;

	// Appends all defined API routes to this socket
	self.api('@api');

	self.on('message', function(msg) {
		switch (msg.TYPE) {
			case 'api':
				// this message is processed automatically
				break;
			case YOUR_KEY:
				break;
		}
	});
}
```

The method creates sends data via WebSocket to Total.js WebSocket API. The method has same functionality like `API()` method.

- Event for all AJAX errors: `ON('error', function(response) {})`
- Event for all AJAX responses: `ON('response', function(response) {})`
- JSON is parsed as `JSON` and JSON dates are converted to `Date` automatically

```js
WAPI(schema, [data], callback, [timeout])
// @schema {String}
// @data {Object} optional
// @callback {Function} or @path {String}
// @timeout {Number}

// Without callback
WAPI('products', 'products.items');

// With dynamic argument "shoes"
WAPI('products/shoes', 'products.items');

// With dynamic argument "shoes" and with query argument
WAPI('products/shoes/?sort=dtcreated_desc', 'products.items');

// With a callback
WAPI('products', function(value, err) {

	if (err) {
		// Error handling
	}

	console.log(value);
});
```

It's an extended `API()` method. This method calls the` API()` method with `DEF.api {String}` URL address, so you don't need to declare the URL address every time.

__Example__:

```js
DEF.api = '/apiv1/';

DAPI('users_remove/12356', function(response) {
	// The method will execute API('/apiv1/ users_remove/123456', ...)
});
```

The method creates an asynchronous request to Total.js Quick API. The method has same functionality like `AJAX()` method.

- CORS is enabled on all URL addresses witch start `http://` or `https://`
- Default AJAX headers are stored in DEF.headers
- Event for all AJAX errors: `ON('error', function(response) {})`
- Event for all AJAX responses: `ON('response', function(response) {})`
- JSON is parsed as `JSON` and JSON dates are converted to `Date` automatically

```js
API(url_schema, [data], callback/path);
// @url_schema {String}
// @data {Object} optional
// @callback {Function} or @path {String}
// returns {API helpers}

// Without callback
API('/apiv1/ products', 'products.items');

// With dynamic argument "shoes"
API('/apiv1/ products/shoes/', 'products.items');

// With dynamic argument "shoes" and with query argument
API('/apiv1/ products/shoes/?sort=dtcreated_desc', 'products.items');

// With a callback
API('/apiv1/ products', function(value, err, response) {

	if (err) {
		// Error handling
	}

	// response.url      {String} URL address
	// response.process  {Boolean} Can disable future processing.
	// response.error    {Boolean} Is error?
	// response.upload   {Boolean} Is upload?
	// response.method   {String} Request method
	// response.data     {Object} Request data
	// response.response {String} Response content
	// response.status   {Number} HTTP status code
	// response.text     {String} HTTP status text
	// response.headers  {Object} Response headers
	// response.duration {Number} Milliseconds

	console.log(value);
});
```

__Total.js API Routing__ was designed to simplify work. Therefore, the structure for `API` routing is straightforward, and you can use it everywhere. __API routing__ can work only with Total.js Schemas and their operations.

__Main topics__:

- [Standard API routing](#)
- [WebSocket API](#)
- [Usage on the client-side](#)

#### Benefits:

- Total.js framework uses only the one `route` in the background (high-speed routing, fewer routes = better performance)
- data can be encrypted additionally
- easy usage
- one API route includes many routes to the operations
- you can use multiple API routes
- supports localization
- supports great error handling
- __RECOMMENDATION__: Total.js supports WebSocket API routes

## :far fa-globe: Standard API routing

### Total.js Routing

```js
// Users
ROUTE('API  /api/   -users_query            *Users    --> query');
ROUTE('API  /api/   -users_read/{id}        *Users    --> read');
ROUTE('API  /api/   +users_insert           *Users    --> check insert (response)');
ROUTE('API  /api/   +users_update/{id}      *Users    --> update');
ROUTE('API  /api/   -users_remove/{id}      *Users    --> remove');

// Products
ROUTE('API  /api/   -products_query         *Products --> query');
ROUTE('API  /api/   -products_read/{id}     *Products --> read');
ROUTE('API  /api/   +products_insert        *Products --> insert');
ROUTE('API  /api/   +products_update/{id}   *Products --> update');
ROUTE('API  /api/   -products_remove/{id}   *Products --> remove');

// ...
```

In the background, the Total.js framework will create only the one route with the same endpoint `/api/` for above routes. All routes are directed to the schemas.

__Request example__:

```request
POST /api/
Content-Type: application/json

{
	"schema": "schema_name/{dynamic_arg_1}/{dynamic_arg_2}?query=arguments",
	"data": {}
}
```

## :far fa-project-diagram: WebSocket API

API routes for WebSocket must contain identifiers in the form `@YOUR_NAME` instead of the relative URL address. So, instead of standard HTTP Requests, you can use WebSocket for communication between UI and your server application. All data are serialized/deserialized in JSON format.

__Example__:

```js
// Users
ROUTE('API  @api   -users_query            *Users    --> query');
ROUTE('API  @api   -users_read/{id}        *Users    --> read');
ROUTE('API  @api   +users_insert           *Users    --> check insert (response)');
ROUTE('API  @api   +users_update/{id}      *Users    --> update');
ROUTE('API  @api   -users_remove/{id}      *Users    --> remove');

// Products
ROUTE('API  @api   -products_query         *Products --> query');
ROUTE('API  @api   -products_read/{id}     *Products --> read');
ROUTE('API  @api   +products_insert        *Products --> insert');
ROUTE('API  @api   +products_update/{id}   *Products --> update');
ROUTE('API  @api   -products_remove/{id}   *Products --> remove');

// ...

// IMPORTANT: socket route
ROUTE('SOCKET / @api');
```

__WebSocket message__:

```js
{
	"TYPE": "api",
	"callbackid": "CUSTOM_CALLBACK_ID", // The value will be returned back
	"data": {
		"schema": "schema_name/{dynamic_arg_1}/{dynamic_arg_2}?query=arguments",
		"data": {}
	}
}
```

## Usage on the client-side

We have extended our [client-side library for creating SPA and reusable components](/components/) by adding new methods:

#### Method `API(url_schema, [data], callback)`

- [Documentation](/components/40d02001ra51c/#612cd001yj51c)

This method sends data to the specific `API` endpoint. The big disadvantage is that you need to add a relative URL endpoint for each call.

```js
API('/api/ users_query?page=2', function(response) {
	console.log('Users:', response);
});
```

#### Method `DAPI(schema, data, callback)`

- [Documentation](/components/40d02001ra51c/#6455d001my51c)

`DAPI` method means __Default API__, and it can work only with the one URL endpoint. In addition, this method wraps the `API()` method in the background with the predefined URL address. When the app is starting, you need to set a default URL API endpoint:

```js
DEF.api = '/api/';
```

__Calls__:

```js
DAPI('users_query?page=2', function(response) {
	console.log('Users:', response);
});

DAPI('users_read/1234', function(response) {
	console.log('User:', response);
});
```

#### Method `WAPI(schema, data, callback)`

- [Documentaion](/components/40d02001ra51c/#b2ee5001yp51c)

`WAPI` method means __WebSocket API__ and it's something like `DAPI()` method. First, you need to initalize WebSocket connection like the example below:

__Initialization__:

```js
// Makes a WebSocket connection
WAPI({ url: '/api/' });
```

__Calls__:

```js
WAPI('users_query?page=2', function(response) {
	console.log('Users:', response);
});

WAPI('users_read/1234', function(response) {
	console.log('User:', response);
});
```

---

If you want to use multiple WebSocket endpoints, then you need to to initialize multiple WebSockets via [`WAPI_INIT(opt)`](/components/40d02001ra51c/#b2ef1001fh51c) method.

__Example__:

```js
// Initialization
var api1 = WAPI_INIT({ url: '/api1/' });
var api2 = WAPI_INIT({ url: '/api2/' });

// Calls
api1.send('users_query?page=2', function(response) {

});

api2.send('users_query?page=2', function(response) {

});
```

