Executes an operation.

```js
OPERATION(name, [value], fn, [options], [controller]);
// @name {String} An operation name or URL address
// @value {Object} A value
// @fn {Function(err, value)} A callback function
// @options {Object} A custom options
// @controller {Controller} A controller instance
```

### External operations

External operations allow you to use a URL address to the specific operation that will be evaluated as a classic operation registered via the `NEWOPERATION()` method.

__https://www.yourdomain.com/operation.js__:

```js
// $ {OperationOptions}
$.succces();
```

__Evaluation__:

```js
// The code will be downloaded once, and it will keep in the memory
OPERATION('https://www.yourdomain.com/operation.js', {}, function(err, response) {
	// do something
});

// Or with 5 minutes expiration, after that, it will be removed automatically
OPERATION('https://www.yourdomain.com/operation.js <5 minutes>', {}, function(err, response) {
	// do something
});
```

__Possible values for expiration:__

- `<5 minutes>`
- `<1 day>`
- `<asap>` expires at the nearest internal service interval

#### An advanced external operation definition

```js
// optional
exports.install = function(next) {

	// @next {Function(err)}
	// The operation won't continue if you execute the "next" argument with the "err" argument.

	setTimeout(next, 1000);
};

// optional
exports.uninstall = function() {
};

exports.make = function($) {

	// $ {OperationOptions}
	$.success();

};
```

Executes task in `TaskBuilder`.

```js
TASK(name, callback, [instance]);
// @name {String} TaskBuilder name + '/' + Task name
// @callback {Function(err, response)} A callback function
// @instance {Object} Optional, Controller or $
// @value {Object} Optional, a value for TaskBuilder
```

```js
TASK('task_builder_name/task_name', function(err, response) {
	console.log(err, response);
});
```

### External tasks

External tasks allow you to use a URL address to the `Task` builder that will be evaluated as a classic Task registered via the `NEWTASK()` method.

__https://www.yourdomain.com/task.js__:

```js
// push {Function(name, fn)}

push('init', function($) {
	$.next('check');
});

push('check', function($) {
	$.success();
});
```

__Evaluation__:

```js
// The code will be downloaded once, and it will keep in the memory
TASK('https://www.yourdomain.com/task.js', 'init', function(err, response) {
	// do something
});

// Or with 5 minutes expiration, after that, it will be removed automatically
TASK('https://www.yourdomain.com/task.js <5 minutes>', 'init', function(err, response) {
	// do something
});
```

__Possible values for expiration:__

- `<5 minutes>`
- `<1 day>`
- `<asap>` expires at the nearest internal service interval

#### An advanced external task definition

```js
// optional
exports.install = function(next) {

	// @next {Function(err)}
	// The task won't continue if you execute the "next" argument with the "err" argument.

	setTimeout(next, 1000);
};

// optional
exports.uninstall = function() {
};

exports.make = function(push) {

	push('init', function($) {
		$.next('check');
	});

	push('check', function($) {
		$.success();
	});

};
```

```js
flow.register(name, callback, [options]);
// @name {String} A component name
// @callback {Function} A component declaration
// @config {Object} A default configuration
// returns FlowInstance;
```

Registers a new component:

```
flow.register('transform', function(exports) {

	exports.message = function(message) {
		switch (message.options.type) {
			case 'uppercase':
				message.data = message.data.toUpperCase();
				break;
			case 'lowercase':
				message.data = message.data.toLowerCase();
				break;
		}

		// Send next
		message.send(0);
	};

}, { type: 'uppercase' });
```

Read more info about properties, methods and delegates above on this page.

`FlowMessage` is generated when the Flow or Flow component sends a message. The message contains a lot of internal information and custom data.

< __IMPORTANT__: Each Flow message must be destroyed via `message.destroy()`!

__Good to know__:

- message must be ended manually via `message.destroy()` method
- message transmits all information about the recipient and sender
- each message is cloned with references to same `events`, `repo` and `data`

```js
flow.register('uppercase', function(instance) {

	// Scope of the component instance
	// ...
	// ...
	// ...

	instance.message = function($) {
		// $ === FlowMessage 
	};

});
```

It's a temporary object for carrying dynamic variables. __Don't use for storing references__ because someone can serialize this object via JSON.

```js
flowmessage.vars;
// returns Object;
```

Alias for `controller.body`

```js
flowmessage.body;
// returns Object;
```

This method registers a new `call` for the Total.js Message Service. We recommend to use this method in some definition file.

- [JSON schema specification](http://json-schema.org)

```js
NEWCALL(name, schema, [callback(data, next)]);
// @name {String} A channel name
// @schema {String/Object} A schema name (JSON schema or Total.js Schema) or raw implementation of valid JSON schema
// @callback {Function(data, next)}
```

__Example with Total.js Schemas__:

```js
NEWCALL('users_insert', '+Users --> insert');
NEWCALL('users_update', '+Users --> update');
```

__Example with Total.js Operations__:

```js
NEWOPERATION('MyOperation', function($) {
	// $.value {Object} - declared JSON schema
	$.succces();
});

NEWCALL('users_query', 'page:String,limit:String', 'MyOperation');

// or external operation:
NEWCALL('users_query', 'page:String,limit:String', 'https://www....com/myoperation.js');
```

__Example with custom handling__:

```js
NEWCALL('users_insert', 'Users', function(data, next) {

	// @data {Object}
	// @next {Function(err, response)}

	// ....
	// ....
	// Do something
	// ....
	// ....

	next(null, { success: true });
});

NEWCALL('users_update', 'Users', function(data, next) {

	// @data {Object}
	// @next {Function(err, response)}

	// ....
	// ....
	// Do something
	// ....
	// ....

	next(null, { success: true });
});

```

This property can replace a root relative path. It's very helpful for applications which are running on the one domain with different paths.

