Creates a new HTTP/HTTPS/SOCKET route.

< :far fa-exclamation-triangle: __IMPORTANT__<br>Use relative URL addresses in __lower-case__.

```js
ROUTE(url, action, [flags], [length])
// @url {String} in the form "METHOD RELATIVE_PATH"
// @action {Function/String} optional, "string" means a name of view
// @flags {String Array} optional, custom flags (timeout is a number)
// @length {Number} optional, max. size of the request body

ROUTE('HTTP_METHOD RELATIVE_PATH');
```

**Supported route flags**
- `10000` any number is considered a max request timeout in miliseconds
- `upload` allows file uploading (processing of `multipart/form–data`)
- `xhr` request headers must contain `XMLHttpRequest` header
- `noxhr` request headers can't conain `XMLHttpRequest` header
- `referer` requet must contain same referer like is request host
- `encrypt` enables client-side encryption
- `nodecrypt` disables client-side decryption
- `mobile` route will be evaluated only for mobile devices
- `robot` route will be evaluated for crawlers or bots
- __NEW__ `csrf` enables CSRF checker (`CONF.secret_csrf` must be filled)


### Authorization

Request authorization is evaluated only via `+` or `-` chars before HTTP method in the URL address. If the route doesn't have declared above declared chars then the action will be evaluated for both - `authorized` or `unauthorized` requests.

< This behaviour is valid for all types of routes with except file routes. File routes must have evaluated authorization manually via [`req.authorize()`](/total4/4047e001ik51c/#4abe0001ji51c) due to performance.

```js
// Request must be authorized
// Look to AUTH() method
ROUTE('+GET /account/');

// Request must be unauthorized
// Look to AUTH() method
ROUTE('-GET /login/');

// It doesn't matter if the request is authorized or unauthorized
ROUTE('GET /terms/');
```

## Schemas routing

- `*User` means name of schema declared in `/schemas/` directory
- `-->` executes operations in a row

```javascript
ROUTE('+POST   /api/account/        *User --> insert');
ROUTE('+POST   /api/account/        *User --> update');
ROUTE('+POST   /api/account/        *User --> save');
ROUTE('+GET    /api/account/        *User --> read');
ROUTE('+DELETE /api/account/        *User --> remove');
ROUTE('+GET    /api/account/        *User --> query');

// With dynamic parameters
// You can use unlimited count of dynamic parameters
// Values can be read via "$.params.category" in the schema operation
ROUTE('GET     /api/products/{category}            *Products --> query');
ROUTE('GET     /api/products/{categoryid:number}/  *Products --> query');

// Chaining
// Or multiple operations with array of results
ROUTE('+POST   /api/account/       *User --> check save email');

// Chaining
// Or multiple operations with the response from "save" operation
ROUTE('+POST   /api/account/       *User --> check save (response) notify');

// RESPOND WITH HTML
ROUTE('GET     /api/products/      *Products --> query', 'VIEW_NAME');
ROUTE('+GET    /api/orders/        *Orders   --> query', 'VIEW_NAME');

// Supports dynamic schemas (so you can merge multiple routes into the one)
// It's case insensitive
// We don't recommend use dynamic schemas due to clarity
ROUTE('GET    /api/{schema}/       *{schema} --> query');
ROUTE('GET    /api/{schema}/{id}/  *{schema} --> read');
ROUTE('POST   /api/{schema}/{id}/  *{schema} --> insert');
ROUTE('PUT    /api/{schema}/{id}/  *{schema} --> update');
```

## Middleware

You can use middlewares declared via `MIDDLEWARE()` method directly in the URL address in the form `&middleware` (of course, you can enter multiple middleware names `&middlewareA &middlewareB`).

```js
ROUTE('GET / &middlewareA &middlewareB');
ROUTE('GET /api/products/  *Products --> query  &middlewareA &middlewareB');
```

## API routing

API routing is a specific part of routing.

```js
ROUTE('API   /apiv1/  +OPERATION_NAME                   *Schema --> operation');
ROUTE('API   /apiv1/  +OPERATION_NAME/PARAM_1/PARAM_N/  *Schema --> operation');
```

- `+OPERATION_NAME`, char `+` means that data will be validated according to the schema
- `-OPERATION_NAME`, char `-` means that data won't by be validated
- `#OPERATION_NAME`, char `#` means `PATCH` functionality

__Example__:

```js
// "+API" means that the request must be authorized
ROUTE('+API  /apiv1/  -customers_query             *Customers --> query');
ROUTE('+API  /apiv1/  -customers_read/id           *Customers --> read');
ROUTE('+API  /apiv1/  -customers_records/id        *Customers --> records');
ROUTE('+API  /apiv1/  -customers_remove/id         *Customers --> remove');
ROUTE('+API  /apiv1/  +customers_insert            *Customers --> insert');
ROUTE('+API  /apiv1/  +customers_update/id         *Customers --> update');

// Dynamic params in operation can contain data-type
// You can use unlimited count of dynamic parameters
// Values can be read via "$.params.category" in the schema operation
ROUTE('+API  /apiv1/  -products_query/id:uid       *Products  --> query');
ROUTE('+API  /apiv1/  -products_query/id:number    *Products  --> query');

// Dynamic arguments are "id" and "category"
ROUTE('+API  /apiv1/  -something/id/category/      *Something --> read');
```

< __Usage on client-side__<br>Client-side jComponent library supports Total.js API via [`API()` method](/components/40d02001ra51c/#612cd001yj51c).

__How does it work on client-side?__

Data are always sent via `POST` method - all the time. The design architecture of Total.js API is created due to performance of evaluating routes and much simple encryption of all sent data.

```html
POST /apiv1/
Content-Type: application/json
```
```json
{
	"schema": "OPERATION_NAME",    // operation name
	// "schema": "OPERATION_NAME/PARAM_1/PARAM_N", // operation name with dynamic parameters
	"data": {},                    // optional, data
	"query": 'parge=1&take=10'     // optional, query arguments
}
```

## WebSocket API routing

__NEW__: WebSocket API routing is a specific part of routing. It has same declaration like `API` routing, but instead of URL address must be defined __API name__ in the form `@api_name`, example:

```js
// API declaration
ROUTE('API   @ws_api_name  +OPERATION_NAME                   *Schema --> operation');
ROUTE('API   @ws_api_name  +OPERATION_NAME/PARAM_1/PARAM_N/  *Schema --> operation');

// Tunnel declaration for the WebSocket communication
ROUTE('SOCKET / @ws_api_name');

// Tunnel declaration for the WebSocket communication with custom handling
ROUTE('SOCKET / @ws_api_name', custom_handling);

function custom_handling() {
	var self = this;
	self.api('ws_api_name');
	// or self.api('@ws_api_name');
	// supports encryption: self.encrypt();
}
```

## Universal routing

```javascript
// Route with flags
ROUTE('POST /relative/', action, ['xhr']);

// Route with flags, middlewares and with the upload limit (1024 kB)
ROUTE('POST /relative/', action, ['&middleware1', '&middleware3', 'upload'], 1024);

// Route with middleware and settings for all middleware
ROUTE('GET /relative/', action, ['&middleware', { name: 'middleware custom options' }]);

// Route with flag + increased timeout to 10 seconds
ROUTE('PUT /relative/', action, [10000]);

// Route without flags and is routed into the view "/views/index.html"
ROUTE('GET /', 'index'); // is same as ROUTE('/');

// Route without flags and is routed into the view in a theme e.g. "/themes/default/views/index.html"
ROUTE('GET /', '=default/index');
ROUTE('GET /', '=?/index'); // --> "=?" means that the framework uses default theme name
ROUTE('GET /', '~index'); // --> "~" means that the framework loads view "index" from root of  "/views/" (skips themes)

// Authorized:
ROUTE('+GET   /authorized/');

// Unauthorized:
ROUTE('-GET  /unauthorized/');
```

### How to handle POST/PATCH/PUT/DELETE data?

We recommend to use Total.js Schemas for processing of request data.

```js
exports.install = function() {
	ROUTE('POST /form/', action_name);
};

function action_name() {
	var self = this; // Controller
	console.log(self.body); // Request payload
	self.success();
}
```

## WebSocket routing

__Route flags for socket__:

- `json` all messages will be serialized/deserialized from/to `JSON` (__default__)
- `text` all messages will be as a plain text
- `binary` message will be as raw buffer

```js
// Example
// File: /controllers/socket.js

exports.install = function() {
	ROUTE('SOCKET /live/', action, ['json']);

	// With Total.js authorization
	// ROUTE('+SOCKET /live/', action, ['json']);
});

function action() {

	var self = this;

	self.autodestroy();

	self.on('open', function(client) {
		// Your code
		client.send({ msg: 'Hello world' });
	});

	self.on('close', function(client) {
		// Your code
	});

	self.on('message', function(client, message) {
		// Your code
		console.log(message);
		client.send({ msg: 'Thank you for your message' });
	});
}
```

## File routing

```js
// Example
// File: /controllers/files.js

exports.install = function() {
	ROUTE('FILE /photos/*.jpg',  action);
	ROUTE('FILE /documents/*.*', action);
});

function action(req, res) {
	// do something
	res.throw404();
}
```

