## Internal error routes

Error routes can defined via HTTP status codes like this:

```js
ROUTE('#400', your_action);
ROUTE('#401', your_action);
ROUTE('#403', your_action);
ROUTE('#404', your_action);
ROUTE('#409', your_action);
ROUTE('#439', your_action);
ROUTE('#500', your_action);
ROUTE('#503', your_action);
```

< We don't recommend creating custom action for `500` HTTP status because if the action contains an error, your application will loop infinitely.

Creates a middleware. The middleware is executed before is executing a `Request`, `Controller`, or `Module`. The middleware has to be specified for usage.

< __Good to know__:<br>We recommend to store all middleware in the `middleware` directory.

```js
NEWMIDDLEWARE(name, fn, [assign], [first]);
// @name {String} The middleware name.
// @fn {Function($)} important (can be null)
// @assign {String/String Array} optional, assign middleware to ...
// @first {Boolean} optional, adds priority before other middleware
```

__Assignment types__:

- `dynamic` means classic routes to schemas or controllers
- `static` means static files
- `socket` means WebSocket routes
- `*` all routes

### Middleware `$` options

```js
NEWMIDDLEWARE('mymiddleware', function($) {

	// IMPORTANT: next processing
	// {Function}
	$.next();

	// Cancel processing
	// IMPORTANT: you need to respond with $.res.SOMETHING()
	// {Function}
	$.cancel();

	// HTTP Request
	// {Object}
	$.req;

	// HTTP response
	// {Object}
	$.res;

	// Route options (may not exists)
	// {Object}
	$.options;

	// Request body data (alias to req.body)
	// {Object}
	$.body;

	// URL query data (alias to req.query)
	// {Object}
	$.query;
	$.filter;

	// User instance (may not exists)
	// {Object}
	$.user;

	// Uploaded files (alias to req.files)
	// {Array Object}
	$.files;

	// Session instance (may not exists)
	// {Object}
	$.session;

	// +v3.3.0: A current session ID
	// {String}
	$.sessionid;

	// Language
	// {String}
	$.language;

	// Controller (may not exists)
	// {Object}
	$.controller;

	// Dynamic routing params (may not exists)
	// {Object}
	$.params;

	// First dynamic param
	// {String}
	$.id;

	// +v3.3.0: Alias to req.headers
	// {Object}
	$.headers;

	// +v3.4.0: Returns parsed User-Agent
	// {String}
	$.ua;

});
```

### How to use middleware for specific types of routes?

```js
// Processes all requests
NEWMIDDLEWARE('mymiddleware', function($) {
	$.next();
}, '*');

// Only for classic routes:
NEWMIDDLEWARE('mymiddleware', function($) {
	$.next();
}, 'dynamic');

// Only for WebSocket routes:
NEWMIDDLEWARE('mymiddleware', function($) {
	$.next();
}, 'socket');

// Only for static files:
NEWMIDDLEWARE('mymiddleware', function($) {
	$.next();
}, 'static');
```

### How to cancel `next` processing?

```js
NEWMIDDLEWARE('mymiddleware', function($) {

	$.res.json({ success: false });
	$.cancel();

});
```

### How to remove middleware?

```js
NEWMIDDLEWARE('mymiddleware', null);
```

### How to use middleware in the routing?

```js
ROUTE('GET /api/users/  *Users --> query  &middleware1 &middleware2 &middleware3');

// or
ROUTE('GET /api/users/', action, ['&middleware1', '&middleware2']);
```

__or__ you can easily add a middleware to all routes:

```js
// Only for dynamic routes
USE('middleware1 middleware2', '*', 'dynamic');

// Only for file routes
USE('middleware1 middleware2', '*', 'file');

// Only for file WebSocket
USE('middleware1 middleware2', '*', 'socket');

// For all requests
USE('middleware1 middleware2');
```

