__Data models__ are defined in Total.js as __Schemas__. __Total.js Schemas__ are the second important part of __Total.js framework__. With schemas, you can control incoming data and convert them to your defined types. Schemas support validation and CRUD operations with custom workflows.

< __IMPORTANT:__<br>Schema isn't a mirror for a table schema in your database! Schema is a pre-defined definition only for incoming data, so incoming data is transformed according to the schema.

## Creating of schema

- a schema can be created via [`NEWSCHEMA()` method](/total4/407ff001jy51c/#49a82001ll51c)
- in most cases, schemas are stored in the `/schemas/` directory
- use camelcase for the name of the schema , e.g. `Account`
- use lowercase for the filename of the schema, e.g. `account`
- you can group similar schemas via  `/` char in the name of the schema, e.g. `Users/Orders`
- use plural names for the schemas that return more then one data item (model)

__Example with schema declaration__:

```js
NEWSCHEMA('Account', function(schema) {

	// Fields definition
	schema.define('name', 'String(30)', true);
	schema.define('email', 'Email', true);
	schema.define('age', Number, val => val > 18 && val < 50);

	// Operations
	schema.setSave(function($, model) {

		// $ {SchemaOptions} --> read more in "Data models -> $" section
		// model {Object}    --> received and transformed data according to this schema

	});

	// ...
	// ...
	// ...
	// ...

});
```

Instead of defining handling functions in the controller, you can create methods in the schemas. You can use pre-defined methods (called CRUD operations) or use `workflow` with a custom name. All operations are optional, so you can choose what is needed for your project and leave out what's not.

< __IMPORTANT__:<br>All data which you will use in the schema operations will be prepared according to the schema, so you will work only with data-types that you define. __Incoming data that is not defined in the schema will be removed from the model!__

__Example with schema operations__:

```js
NEWSCHEMA('Account', function(schema) {

	// Fields definition
	schema.define('name', 'String(30)', true);
	// ...
	// ...
	// ...

	// Pre-defined
	schema.setQuery(function($) { /* ... */ });
	schema.setRead(function($) { /* ... */ });
	schema.setSave(function($, model) { /* ... */ });
	schema.setInsert(function($, model) { /* ... */ });
	schema.setUpdate(function($, model) { /* ... */ });
	schema.setPatch(function($, model) { /* ... */ });
	schema.setRemove(function($) { /* ... */ });

	// Custom workflows
	schema.addWorkflow('custom_name1', function($) { /* ... */ });
	schema.addWorkflow('custom_nameN', function($) { /* ... */ });

});
```

## Data types

Schemas support various data types which you can use in the schema definition. Some data types are under special validation like `UID`, `Email`, `JSON`, `Base64`, `Phone` or `Date`. Read more in [`schema.define()` method](/total4/40d13001eh51c/#4dd56001rb51c).

- `String` or `String(MAX_LENGTH)`
- `Number` supports fixed numbers or decimals
- `Number2` supports fixed numbers or decimals, and a default value is `null`
- `Lowercase` or `Lowercase(MAX_LENGTH)` - value will be in lower case
- `Uppercase` or `Uppercase(MAX_LENGTH)` - value will be in UPPER CASE
- `Capitalize` or `Capitalize(MAX_LENGTH)` - value will be in Camel Case
- `Capitalize2` or `Capitalize2(MAX_LENGTH)` - first char in value will be in Upper case
- `Name` or `Name(MAX_LENGTH)` - capitalize every word, value won't contain numbers and special chars except spaces
- `UID` means - Total.js unique identifier
- `Boolean`
- `JSON`
- `Base64`
- `Email`
- `ZIP`
- `URL`
- `Phone`
- `Object`
- `Date`

:warning: __Default values__:

- `String` - the default value of all string types is `''` (empty string)
- `Number` the default value of all number types is `0` (zero)
- `Boolean` the default value of all boolean types is `false`
- `Object` the default value of all object types is `null`
- `Date` the default value of all date types is `null`

## Custom validation

You can provide custom validation easily with the `schema.define()` method:

```js
schema.define('age', Number, (val, model) => val > 18 && val < 50);
```

This method sends data from an instance defined in the path, but the `message` delegate in the component instance (defined in the path) isn't executed.

```js
flow.send(path, body);
// @path {String} in the form "INSTANCE-ID__OUTPUT-INDEX"
// @body {Object}
// return Boolean;

// Usage:
flow.send('INSTANCEID__OUTPUTINDEX', { hello: 'message' });
```

The method performs several steps:

- unloads all instances
- unloads all components
- loads all components
- loads all instances

```js
