__Total.js framework__ has a built-in unit-testing mechanism for your application and your utilities. With testing, you can quickly check if your route is working correctly or not returning expected output.

### Basics

All test file should be declared inside `/tests/` directory inside your application. You need to access global `TESTER()` to every test file requires `total4` package. After that you can declare your unit tests.

```js
// Example
// File: {app}/tests/users.js

require('total4');

TESTER(function(group, start) {
	group('Users', function(test, cleanup) {
		test('Create', function(next) {
			RESTBuilder.POST('/users/', { email: 'abc@def.ijk' }).exec(function(err, res) {
				err ? next(err) : next();
			});

			// Shorthand
			RESTBuilder.POST('/users/', { email: 'abc@def.ijk' }).exec(next);
		});
	});

	start();
});
```

### Usage

Callback of `TESTER()` is returning `group()` and `start()` functions where we can start creating our tests. Grouping of tests is currently required even if you want just one test declaration. Tester is executing one group and one test in that group at the time. If one test fails, tester throws an exception.

### Groups & Tests

Group has two required arguments. Name of declared group (will be printed into output console) and handler. Handler is returning `test()` and `cleanup()` functions.

To declare your test use `test()` with two arguments:
	- Optional name (If first argument is `Function` it won't be printed into output console)
	- Required handler to evaluate your test. If first argument is truthy, tester will evaluate this as unsuccessful test and throws an exception.

### Start

To start your tests use `start()` from `TESTER()` callback. This function has also callback which will be triggered when ALL tests was successful. Test files are simple node files which can be executed manually

### Clean up

There is also optional `cleanup()` function inside every group. Function is triggered when group was successfully or even unsuccessfully completed. If one of your test failed, cleanup callback will be called with error as a first argument. You can use this function to manually remove newly created rows from your database when something unexpected happened or group was tester successfully.

```js
cleanup(function(err) {

	if (err) {
		// test failed
	} else {
		// test done
	}

	// do something

});
```

### Example

[Github repository](https://github.com/totaljs/examples/blob/master/tester/)

The method can set a new value to the specific method in components.

```js
SETTER([wait], selector, propOrMethod, [argA], [argB], [..argN]);
// @wait {Boolean} Optional, it will wait for the given component(selector argument) to be initialized
// @selector {String}
// @propOrMethod {String} Property or Method name (can't be nested)
// @argA {Object} Optional, additional argument
// @argB {Object} Optional, additional argument
// @..argN {Object} Optional, additional argument

SETTER('#loading', 'hide', 1000);
// Executes --> FIND('#loading').hide(1000);

SETTER('textbox', 'set', 'NEW VALUE');
// Executes --> FIND('textbox').set('NEW VALUE');

SETTER('textbox@1', 'set', 'NEW VALUE');
// Executes --> FIND('textbox@1').set('NEW VALUE');

SETTER(true, 'loading', 'show');
// +v9.0.0 It will wait for a "loading" component to be initialized and then executes --> FIND('loading').show();

SETTER($('#container'), 'reconfigure', 'icon:home');
// +v11.4.0 supports jQuery element or DOM element

SETTER('!datepicker', 'hide');
// +v17
// It executes `hide` if the component has been loaded
// It's targeted for LAZY components

// +v18 supports shorter notations:
SETTER('loading/show');
SETTER('!datepicker/hide');
```

