The editor allows the user design app design from the existing objects defined in the template.

## Editor vs Render

The editor supports two modes:

- `editor` mode for editing
- `render` compilation

The differences between modes are not big, but important. Render mode downloads all objects (their `render` implementation) into the template directly. The `render` implementation doesn't contain settings.

## Editor variables and settings

You can use the paths below in the Object settings as a data source for some DropDown lists.

- `DEF.cl.outputs` path contains all outputs
- `DEF.cl.inputs` path contains all inputs
- `DEF.cl.paths` contains Paths + Components with `.follow = true`
- `DEF.cl.codes` path contains code lists (the content depends on the settings)
- `DEF.cl.list` contains a list of all instances
- `DEF.cl.views` contains a list of data views
- `DEF.cl.datasource` contains all CodeList + Components with `.follow = true`
- `DEF.cl.apps` contains App list

All above paths must contain data in the form:

```js
[
	{
		id: String,
		name: String,  // a humanable text
		type: String   // only for Paths
	}
]
```

## Editor requests

The editor makes requests from the client-side only, so your server must have enabled CORS for our domain.

---

### Paths

The endpoint must return a list of all available paths. The object knows where to read and save data.

__The response must be in the form:__

```js
[
	id: String,    // a path
	name: String,  // a humanable text
	type: String   // optional
]
```

---

### Codes

The endpoint must return a list of all available code lists. What is it? Just imagine that in your app is a possibility to select e.g., City, Country from some list, and some objects support option "Choose a code list".

__The response must be in the form__:

```js
[
	id: String,    // code list id
	name: String   // a humanable text
]
```

__How to use codes in the app__?

Your master app must have implemented delegates below:

```js
UIBuilder.clfind = function(clid, search, callback) {

	// @clid {String}
	// @search {String} optional, it can be empty
	// @callback {Function(response)}

	// Response must be always in the form:
	var response = [];
	response.push({ id: 'totaljs', name: 'Total.js' });
	response.push({ id: 'expressjs', name: 'Express.js' });

	callback(response);

};

UIBuilder.clread = function(clid, id, callback) {

	// @clid {String}
	// @id {String} required
	// @callback {Function(response)}

	// Response must be always in the form or null:
	response = { id: 'totaljs', name: 'Total.js' };

	callback(response);
};
```

Delegates `.clfind` and `.clread` are part of the application object or you can define them globally in the `UIBuilder` object.

---

### Data Views

The endpoint must return a list of all available data views (data sources).

__The response must be in the form__:

```js
[
	id: String,     // code list id
	name: String,   // a humanable text
	type: String    // supported types: list, dashboard
]
```

---

### Upload

This endpoint allows you to upload some files directly from the editor. For the making of upload, you can use the [`FileUploader`](https://componentator.com/components/j-fileuploader/) component.

__The response must be in the form__:

```js
[
	{
		id: String,     // file id
		url: String,    // absolute link for downloading
		name: String,   // file name
		ext: String,    // file extension
		size: Number,   // file sizes in bytes
		width: Number,  // optional, width
		height: Number  // optional, height
	}
]
```

---

### Save

The editor will send data to your API endpoint in the form:

```
// POST https://yourserver.com/save/
// content-type: application/json
{
	data: { ... }
}
```

Components must specified in the [Template](/uibuilder/swhc001cs41d/).

- [Learn from existing components](https://github.com/totaljs/uibuildercomponents)

---

__How can I load my components into the UI Builder editor?__

UI Builder editor works only with the component implementation targeted for the editor. So, the source for the UI Builder must be the __editor.html__ file.

![Custom component](/download/ysqu001ro41d-1pa92l3-200x222-1.png)

## Metadata

You must store component metadata in the independent file, e.g., `layout.html`, for every component.

```js
// Important: A component identifier
exports.id = 'layout';

// Important: A component name
exports.name = '2 columns layout';

// Important: Only for editor
exports.group = 'Layouts';

// Component author
exports.author = 'Total.js';

// A default configuration
exports.config = { resize: true };

// Total.js Font Icon
exports.icon = 'ti ti-columns';

// External dependencies (links to scripts or styles)
exports.import = [];

// Optional, fixed defined styles or the styles can be declared in <style> element
exports.css = '';

// The source-code will be used for publishing
// If the "render" is not specified then component won't be compiled for render
exports.render = 'https://domain.com/components/layout/render.html';

// Optional, URL address for the settings form
exports.settings = 'https://..../settings.html';

// Optional, for what kind of app is the component targeted?
// Current supported types: app, mobile, flowboard, uicomponents, hmi
exports.type = ['app', 'dashboard'];

// The user will see the component in the settings form Path for reading/writing (only for UI designer)
exports.follow = true;

// The component will be hidden in the component list
exports.hidden = true;

// NEW
// The component can contains additional external UI Builder components
exports.components = {
	input: 'url or base64',
	button: 'url or base64'
};

// IMPORTANT:
exports.make = function(instance, config, element, cls) {

	// @instance {Component}

};

// Optional
exports.uninstall = function() {
	// Component is uninstalled
	// You can perform clean up
};
```

This method replaces all dynamic arguments in the form `Hello {args.key}!` in the input `string`.

```js
instance.replace(str, [data]);
// @str {String}
// @data {Object} optional, additional object data
// return {String}
```

__Possible variables__:

- `{args.key}` read from the `app.args`
- `{query.key}` read from the current URL address
- `{user.key}` read from the `window.user` object
- `{data.key}` read from the input data

This method reads a value according the `path` from the input `object`.

```js
instance.read(obj, path);
// @obj {Object}
// @path {String}
// return {Object}
```

This method writes a `value` according the `path` to the input `object`.

```js
instance.write(obj, path);
// @obj {Object}
// @path {String}
// @value {Object}
```

This method reads a state.

```js
instance.get([type]);
// @type {String} optional, default "value"
// return {Boolean/Object}
```

__Types__:

- `value` returns `{Object}` (current value)
- `disabled` returns `{Boolean}`
- `affected` returns `{Boolean}`
- `modified` returns `{Boolean}`
- `readonly` returns `{Boolean}`

This method sets a state and emits `set` events in the current + all parent objects.

```js
instance.set(type, value);
// @type {String}
// @value {Boolean/Object}
```

__Types__:

- `value` sets `{Object}` as a current value
- `disabled` sets `{Boolean}`
- `affected` sets `{Boolean}`
- `modified` sets `{Boolean}`
- `readonly` sets `{Boolean}`

This method returns all nested objects (their instances).

```js
instance.family();
// return {Array}
```

This method determines if the object element is hidden or not.

```js
instance.hidden();
// return {Boolean}
```

This method registers an input for incoming data. All inputs must be declared in the `exports.inputs` property, in metadata.

```js
instance.input(id, callback);
// @id {String} input ID
// @callback {Function(data)}
```

__Example__:

```js
// ...
exports.inputs = [{ id: 'load', name: 'Load data' }];
// ...

exports.make = function(instance) {

	// ...

	instance.input('load', function(data) {
		// Loads data
	});
};
```

This method __registers an output__. The output must be declared in `exports.outputs`.

```js
instance.output(id, callback);
// @id {String} output ID
// @callback {Function(next)}
```

__Example__:

```js
// ...
exports.outputs = [{ id: 'submit', name: 'Submit data' }];
// ...

exports.make = function(instance) {

	// ...

	instance.output('submit', function(next) {
		// next {Function(err, data)}
		next(null, instance.get());
	});

};
```

This method __executes an output__. The output must be declared in `exports.outputs`.

```js
instance.output(id);
// @id {String} output ID
```

__Example__:

```js
// ...
exports.outputs = [{ id: 'submit', name: 'Submit data' }];
// ...

exports.make = function(instance) {

	// ...

	// Executes output
	instance.output('submit');

};
```

This method loads data from a code list according to `clid`.

```js
instance.clfind(clid, search, callback);
// @clid {String} Code list ID
// @search {String} optional, a search phrase
// @callback {Function(array)}
```

__Example__:

```js
exports.make = function(instance) {

	instance.clfind('users', 'Peter', function(response) {
		// @response {Array Object}
	});

};
```

### FAQ

::: How to obtain list of codes?

You can specify the URL endpoint in the Editor settings for obtaining a list of your supported codes. The endpoint must return `{Array}` in the form:

```js
[
	{
		id: 'countries',
		name: 'Countries'
	},
	{
		id: 'cities',
		name: 'Cities'
	}
]
```

You can obtain a list of codes from the `DEF.cl.codes` property for the Object settings.
:::

::: How can I declare codes in the render?

First, you must obtain instance of your `app`. The `app` supports a delegate called `.clfind()`:

```js
app.clfind(function(clid, search, callback) {
	// E.g. "GET /codelists/users/?search=Peter"
	AJAX(QUERIFY('GET /codelists/{0}/'.format(clid), { search: search }), callback);
});
```
:::

