< __Are you Total.js developer?__<br>If you want to use the Total.js framework for your OpenPlatform application, then continue/download with the [__Total.js OpenPlatform app template__](https://github.com/totaljs/openplatform-application) and skip the steps below. __Be careful:__ URL address must be the same as is defined in `openplatform.json`.

__Good to know__:

- each OpenPlatform application is running under __`<iframe>`__ element
- create SPA (single page application) as OpenPlatform application
- make all requests from the client-side asynchronously
- cookies won't work in your OpenPlatform applications

OpenPlatform provides a client-side script for capturing events and calling some OpenPlatform methods directly. You can easily inject it to your web app. The script does not require any dependencies because it's written in vanilla script.

::: __How do I inject OpenPlatform into a client-side script?__

The script below injects OpenPlatform client-side script automatically into your app.

```js
(function() {
	var args = location.search.substring(1).split('&');

	var openplatform = '';

	for (var m of args) {
		if (m.substring(0, 13) === 'openplatform=') {
			openplatform = decodeURIComponent(m.substring(13));
			break;
		}
	}

	if (openplatform) {
		var origin = openplatform.substring(0, openplatform.indexOf('/', 10) + 1);
		if (origin) {
			var scr = document.createElement('SCR' + 'IPT');
			scr.setAttribute('src', origin + 'iframe.js');
			document.body.appendChild(scr);
		}
	} else {
		// not found
	}

})();
```

After the app is ready for use, the following function will be executed.

```js
window.APP_INIT = function() {
	// Optional
	// The app is ready
};
```
:::

::: Do I need to inject the client-side script?
No, it's optional.
:::

