The Flow can handle external requests from 3rd parties in 2 ways.

- [Notify endpoint](#)
- [Proxy path](#)

## Notify endpoint

The notify endpoint can process data very easily and quickly, but has limited functionality. The endpoint sends data automatically to the Flow Designer (if someone has it open). Endpoint must be designed in the form:

- `https://yourflow.com/notify/FLOWSTREAMID-INSTANCEID-PARAM0-PARAM1-PARAMN/`
	- `FLOWSTREAMID` required, where a data 
	- `INSTANCEID` optional
	- `PARAM0` ... `PARAMN` optional

If you visit the endpoint, the Flow will call the `instance.notify()` method in the specific instance (if it's mentioned) with data in the form:

```js
instance.notify = function(data) {
	// data.id {String}              optional, instance id
	// data.method {String}          HTTP method (GET or POST)
	// data.headers {Object}         Request headers
	// data.query {Object}           Parsed URL query arguments
	// data.body {Object}            Parsed body, supported URL Encoded or JSON content type
	// data.url {String}             URL address
	// data.ip {String}              IP address
	// data.params {String Array}    optional, custom params (look at URL address)
};
```

- [Read source code](https://github.com/totaljs/flow/blob/master/controllers/api.js#L137)
- [Client-side usage](https://github.com/totaljs/flowstreamcomponents/blob/main/components/oauth2.html#L151)

__Custom query arguments__:

- `REDIRECT=absolute_URL_address` the browser will be redirect to the address defined in the `REDIRECT` arguments

If you don't specify `REDIRECT` argument, HTML performs `window.close()` method on the client-side. 

## Proxy path

The proxy path creates a real proxy between the main process and the FlowStream worker. All requests within a specific path will be moved to the worker and processed there. If you want to handle requests, you need to register routes via [`ROUTE()`](/total4/40d57002oi50c/) method. The method is part of the [Total.js framework](/total4/).

__Where to define a proxy path?__

![Flow Proxy Path](/download/10nq1001dx51d-1wwanm-823x562-1.jpg)

It makes a condition for permissions. It's designed for our Total.js permission system. It is only compatible with PostgreSQL.

```js
// builder.permit(name, type, value, [useridfield], [userid], [required]);
// @name {String} a field name
// @type {String} a permission type (C create, R read, W write, D delete)
// @value {String Array} list of user permissions
// @userid {String} optional, current user id
// @required {Boolean} optional, permissions must be set (default: true)
// returns {QueryBuilder}
```

__PostgreSQL__:

```
-- Data-Type VARCHAR ARRAY
permissions _text
```

__Permissions are stored like this:__

```js
['C@admin', 'W@admin', 'R@admin', 'D@admin', 'R123456', 'R#employees']
```

- first char e.g. `C` means a permission, in this case:
	- `C` create
	- `R` read
	- `U` update
	- `D` delete
- second char `@` means a role name, so e.g. `@admin` means `admin` role
- second char `#` means a group name, so e.g. `#employees` means `employees` group
- otherwise it means  __user identifier__, e.g. `R123456` is a user with id `123456`

__Example__:

```js
var mypermissions = ['@admin', '123456', '#employees'];
var myuserid = '654321';

// Tries to find all records with "R"userrolegroup, e.g. "R@admin", "@R123456" or "R#employees"
builder.permit('permissions', 'R', permissions);

// Tries to find all records with "R"userrolegroup, "W"userrolegroup, "D"userrolegroup
// A record must contain just the one permission type
builder.permit('permissions', 'RWD', permissions);

// Tries to find all records with "R"userrolegroup or user records
builder.permit('permissions', 'R', permissions, myuserid);
```

